# =============================================================================
# Model: glm-4.7-flash:opencode_no_think
# Base:  glm-4.7-flash-max-ctx:latest (29.9B MoE-lite, Q4_K_M)
# GPU:   Tesla P40, 23040 MiB VRAM
# Built: 2026-05-02
#
# PURPOSE
# -------
# Optimised for opencode and similar agentic tool-use harnesses.
# Corrects the original model's num_ctx which was close to the VRAM ceiling
# but not precisely calibrated. Adds opencode-compatible system instructions.
#
# ORIGINAL MODEL (glm-4.7-flash-max-ctx:latest)
# ----------------------------------------------
#   num_ctx    43000   — user-set, believed to be VRAM limit (close, but not exact)
#   temperature    1   — kept as-is (GLM trained at temp=1, see note below)
#
# CHANGES FROM glm-4.7-flash-max-ctx:latest
# ------------------------------------------
# 1. num_ctx 43520  (was 43000)
#    Benchmarked the exact VRAM cliff on P40. The cliff falls between 43520
#    and 44032 — so 43520 is the true maximum that stays fully in VRAM.
#    The original 43000 was correct in intent but left 520 tokens unused.
#
# 2. temperature 1 — kept unchanged
#    GLM-4.7-flash was trained at temperature=1 and performs consistently
#    there. Tests comparing temp=1 vs temp=0.6 showed no improvement in
#    tool-call JSON reliability at lower temperature (both had ~1/5 runs with
#    non-empty content; the SYSTEM instruction below is the real fix).
#
# 3. SYSTEM — explicit empty-content instruction
#    At both temperature settings, GLM occasionally adds a brief preamble
#    in the content field alongside tool calls ("I'll read the file for you.",
#    etc.). The instruction below eliminates this reliably.
#
# NOTE: GLM does not have a /no_think token like Qwen3. GLM-4.7-flash is
# already a "flash" variant — its thinking overhead is minimal. The _no_think
# suffix here signals the same intent (fast, direct tool use) for naming
# consistency with the qwen3-coder variants.
#
# BENCHMARK — Tesla P40, 2026-05-02
# ----------------------------------
# Generation speed sweep (num_predict=200, short prompt):
#
#   num_ctx   gen tok/s   prompt tok/s   notes
#   -------   ---------   ------------   -----
#     8192       35.66         453.34    fully in VRAM
#    16384       35.65         455.54    fully in VRAM
#    24576       35.58         453.67    fully in VRAM
#    32768       35.49         452.20    fully in VRAM
#    40960       35.25         453.47    fully in VRAM
#    43000       35.57         454.39    fully in VRAM  (original setting)
#    43520       35.71         —         fully in VRAM  ← chosen (true ceiling)
#    44032       26.33         —         partial CPU offload — cliff starts here
#    45056       26.12         —         partial CPU offload
#    49152       19.80         412.64    partial CPU offload
#    57344       17.40         313.97    partial CPU offload
#
# TOOL-CALL TESTS (all passed)
# ----------------------------
#   ✓ Basic single tool call            — empty content, correct args
#   ✓ Parallel tool calls               — combined into one smart bash command
#   ✓ opencode system prompt override   — behaves correctly when system replaced
#   ~ Occasional non-empty content      — ~1/5 runs without SYSTEM instruction;
#                                         SYSTEM instruction below fixes this
# =============================================================================

FROM glm-4.7-flash-max-ctx:latest

# 43520 = true VRAM ceiling on P40 (cliff begins at 44032).
# 520 tokens more than the original 43000 setting.
PARAMETER num_ctx 43520

# Kept at 1 — GLM-4.7-flash was trained at this temperature and is consistent.
# Lowering to 0.6 showed no improvement in tool-call reliability.
PARAMETER temperature 1

SYSTEM """You are an expert software engineer assistant. Follow all tool-use instructions exactly as specified. Use the tools provided to read, write, and execute code. Respond concisely with working solutions.
IMPORTANT: When making tool calls, the message content MUST be empty. Do not narrate, explain, or announce what you are about to do — output only the tool call."""
